      {
        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from stochastic gradient descent (SGD)?",
        "assistant": "Gradient descent and stochastic gradient descent differ mainly in **how they compute the gradient at each step**.\n\n**Gradient descent**, often called **batch gradient descent**, computes the gradient using the **entire dataset** before making one parameter update.\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nBecause it uses all training examples, each update is accurate but can be slow for large datasets.\n\n**Stochastic gradient descent (SGD)** computes the gradient using **one training example at a time**, or sometimes a very small sample, and updates the parameters immediately.\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J_i(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nWhere \\(J_i(\\theta)\\) is the loss for a single training example.\n\nKey differences:\n\n| Method | Gradient computed from | Update frequency | Pros | Cons |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Gradient descent | Entire dataset | Once per full dataset pass | Stable, accurate direction | Slow for large datasets |\n| SGD | One example at a time | Very frequent | Faster, scalable, can escape shallow local minima | Noisy updates, less stable |\n\nIn short: **gradient descent uses the full dataset to take smoother, more precise steps, while SGD uses individual examples to take faster but noisier steps.**",
