      {
        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from simulated annealing?",
        "assistant": "**Gradient descent** and **simulated annealing** are both optimization methods, but they work very differently.\n\n## Gradient Descent\n\nGradient descent uses the **gradient**, or derivative, of the objective function to decide which direction to move.\n\nIt updates parameters by moving downhill:\n\n\\[\n\\theta = \\theta - \\alpha \\nabla J(\\theta)\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n\n- \\(\\theta\\) = current parameters\n- \\(\\alpha\\) = learning rate\n- \\(\\nabla J(\\theta)\\) = gradient of the objective or loss function\n\nGradient descent is best suited for problems where:\n\n- The function is differentiable\n- The variables are continuous\n- You can compute or estimate gradients efficiently\n\nIt is a **local optimization method**, meaning it may get stuck in a local minimum.\n\n---\n\n## Simulated Annealing\n\nSimulated annealing is a **probabilistic optimization method** inspired by the physical process of cooling metals.\n\nInstead of always moving downhill, it sometimes allows moves that make the objective worse. This helps it escape local minima.\n\nThe probability of accepting a worse move depends on a **temperature** parameter:\n\n- At high temperature, worse moves are accepted more often\n- At low temperature, the algorithm becomes more conservative\n- Over time, the temperature is gradually reduced\n\nA typical acceptance probability is:\n\n\\[\nP = e^{-\\Delta E / T}\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n\n- \\(\\Delta E\\) = how much worse the new solution is\n- \\(T\\) = temperature\n\n---\n\n## Key differences\n\n| Feature | Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|---|---|---|\n| Uses gradients? | Yes | No |\n| Type of method | Deterministic or nearly deterministic | Probabilistic |\n| Can accept worse moves? | Usually no | Yes |\n| Good for continuous variables? | Yes | Yes |\n| Good for discrete/combinatorial problems? | Not usually | Yes |\n| Risk of local minima | Can get stuck | Better at escaping |\n| Speed | Often faster | Often slower |\n| Requires differentiability? | Yes | No |\n\n---\n\n## Intuition\n\nGradient descent is like walking downhill in the steepest direction you can find. If you end up in a small valley, you may stay there even if a deeper valley exists elsewhere.\n\nSimulated annealing is like wandering around a landscape while gradually becoming less willing to climb uphill. Early on, it explores widely; later, it settles into a good low point.\n\n---\n\n## In short\n\n**Gradient descent** uses slope information to move directly downhill.\n\n**Simulated annealing** uses random exploration and sometimes accepts worse solutions to avoid getting trapped in local minima.\n\nGradient descent is usually preferred for large differentiable machine learning problems, while simulated annealing is useful for difficult search or combinatorial optimization problems where gradients are unavailable or the objective landscape is highly irregular.",
